WEBVTT

00:06.443 --> 00:09.146
Heavy fighting continues
today in Northern Iraq,

00:09.147 --> 00:12.382
as Kurdish Peshmerga
try to dislodge fighters

00:12.383 --> 00:14.117
from the so-called Islamic State, or ISIS,

00:14.118 --> 00:17.588
from areas around the
oil-rich city of Kirkuk.

00:17.589 --> 00:20.057
A delegation from the newly
created government of Iraq

00:20.058 --> 00:21.425
has arrived in the Capitol.

00:21.426 --> 00:22.659
They'll be meeting

00:22.660 --> 00:24.361
with Secretary of State Elizabeth McCord

00:24.362 --> 00:26.129
before moving on to the White House

00:26.130 --> 00:29.900
to appeal for more help in
their fight against the insurgent

00:29.901 --> 00:31.768
Sunni Islamist group ISIS.

00:31.769 --> 00:33.270
Their request comes

00:33.271 --> 00:36.273
against the backdrop of insurgent gains

00:36.274 --> 00:38.041
in the Anbar Province,

00:38.042 --> 00:39.876
the scene of some of the heaviest fighting

00:39.877 --> 00:43.513
during the U.S.'s ten-year
engagement in Iraq.

00:43.514 --> 00:45.649
Marines took heavy losses
in two separate battles

00:45.650 --> 00:47.751
to wrest control of Fallujah

00:47.752 --> 00:49.586
from Sunni insurgents in 2004,

00:49.587 --> 00:52.088
but now the city is
effectively ruled by ISIS.

00:52.928 --> 00:56.159
President Dalton is reportedly
weighing whether to redeploy

00:56.160 --> 00:58.662
U.S. troops in what the
administration insists...

00:58.663 --> 00:59.663
Morning.

00:59.664 --> 01:01.131
Hey.

01:01.132 --> 01:02.799
Uh-oh.

01:02.800 --> 01:05.702
The Serious Mom face.

01:05.703 --> 01:08.939
- No.
- So, uh...

01:08.940 --> 01:12.943
be honest, how worried
should I be about ISIS?

01:12.944 --> 01:15.312
You let me worry about ISIS.

01:15.313 --> 01:18.048
You worry about getting
your dad up at 7:00.

01:18.049 --> 01:20.283
- He's got a flight to catch.
- All right, fine.

01:20.284 --> 01:21.618
Keep your walls up.

01:21.619 --> 01:23.853
What are you talking about?

01:23.854 --> 01:26.022
We talk about stuff all the time.

01:26.023 --> 01:27.257
What are you doing today?

01:27.258 --> 01:29.225
Work, obviously.

01:29.226 --> 01:31.061
Oh. Right.

01:31.062 --> 01:32.996
So, do they have a, um,

01:32.997 --> 01:35.031
a dress code there, or is it...

01:35.032 --> 01:36.466
- Mom!
- What?

01:36.467 --> 01:38.735
Okay, okay, I will let it go,

01:38.736 --> 01:41.805
because you have a really big
day with the Iraqis, but...

01:41.806 --> 01:43.706
just for the sake of world peace,

01:43.707 --> 01:47.043
can you please promise me that
you'll be a little bit less

01:47.044 --> 01:48.645
passive-aggressive when you talk to them?

01:48.646 --> 01:51.381
That outfit just doesn't say
"front of the house” to me.

01:51.382 --> 01:52.982
There... all aggressive, no passive.

01:52.983 --> 01:55.251
- Mom, I know what I'm doing. I mean...
- I know.

01:55.252 --> 01:57.453
- You look very cute.
- Thank you.

01:57.454 --> 01:59.322
Just a little casual.

01:59.323 --> 02:00.089
Stop.

02:00.090 --> 02:02.157
Stopping.

02:06.863 --> 02:08.798
Good morning, ma'am.

02:08.799 --> 02:10.532
Normally, I'm the first one in,

02:10.533 --> 02:13.035
but this is the... fifth day in a row

02:13.036 --> 02:14.504
you've gotten here before me.

02:14.505 --> 02:17.740
Just prepping my remarks
for the Iraqi delegation.

02:17.741 --> 02:19.809
Isn't that mostly a photo op?

02:19.810 --> 02:21.911
Is there something wrong
with what Matt worked up?

02:21.912 --> 02:24.646
Can I help you with something, Nadine?

02:25.414 --> 02:27.650
I know you've been getting here early

02:27.651 --> 02:29.619
to investigate Secretary Marsh.

02:29.620 --> 02:31.821
There was very little about him

02:31.822 --> 02:33.689
that I didn't know, so...

02:33.690 --> 02:35.357
maybe I could help you.

02:35.358 --> 02:37.725
All right.

02:39.195 --> 02:41.530
Why, on the last day of his life,

02:41.531 --> 02:44.433
did he change his itinerary
and fly to Venezuela?

02:44.434 --> 02:47.503
He said he had family business to tend to.

02:47.504 --> 02:49.872
Could that have been a
cover for something else?

02:49.873 --> 02:53.442
Maybe something about his
plans to run for president?

02:53.443 --> 02:55.511
Maybe he was meeting with future donors

02:55.512 --> 02:57.546
or fundr...

02:57.547 --> 03:01.283
Oh, Nadine, I'm...

03:01.284 --> 03:03.985
I'm really sorry.

03:07.022 --> 03:09.691
You're certain he was planning to run?

03:09.692 --> 03:11.659
Yeah.

03:12.294 --> 03:14.730
Well...

03:14.731 --> 03:16.899
I don't know why he went to Venezuela,

03:16.900 --> 03:19.902
other than what he told me...
which was probably a lie.

03:19.903 --> 03:22.770
And I'm certainly a fool, so...

03:24.640 --> 03:27.509
...I suppose I can't help you after all.

03:27.510 --> 03:29.910
Excuse me.

03:32.514 --> 03:34.054
Every six months, there's
a protocol breakfast

03:34.055 --> 03:35.721
- for the new Foreign Service officers...
- Uh-huh.

03:35.722 --> 03:36.640
...where they learn the food etiquette

03:36.641 --> 03:37.913
- of their new postings.
- Wow.

03:37.914 --> 03:39.833
Seems like a solid use of taxpayer dollars.

03:39.834 --> 03:40.716
Come on, let's hurry up.

03:40.717 --> 03:42.123
Like if you find yourself in Denmark

03:42.124 --> 03:43.356
and you're served ymer,

03:43.357 --> 03:45.193
you shouldn't complain that
it tastes like sour milk.

03:45.194 --> 03:46.361
What's ymer?

03:46.362 --> 03:47.896
Sour milk. The point is, you should

03:47.897 --> 03:49.664
be prepared to eat your ymer like a native.

03:49.665 --> 03:50.344
Oh? How's that?

03:50.345 --> 03:52.094
- On kammerjunker, obviously.
- Obviously.

03:52.095 --> 03:53.304
Look, just forget about the ymer.

03:53.305 --> 03:54.828
You're the one who keeps
bringing it up the ymer.

03:54.829 --> 03:56.096
What we're here for, my good man,

03:56.097 --> 03:57.602
- are the Chinese pork dumplings.
- I can't...

03:57.603 --> 03:59.114
They're pretty much the best in the world.

03:59.115 --> 04:02.911
So be cool and act like you're
in the Foreign Service, okay?

04:02.912 --> 04:04.770
Wait... why aren't you eating dumplings?

04:04.771 --> 04:06.014
They're not all gone, are they?

04:06.015 --> 04:07.415
God, I told you to walk faster!

04:07.416 --> 04:08.483
I've had no coffee.

04:08.484 --> 04:10.184
Okay, actually, Win is getting them for me.

04:10.185 --> 04:11.819
Win?

04:11.820 --> 04:14.155
Win, as in Win your fiancé?

04:14.156 --> 04:15.623
Yes, and he wants to meet you.

04:15.624 --> 04:18.860
Yes, and that's not going to happen.

04:18.861 --> 04:20.361
Wait, wait, you guys talk about me?

04:20.362 --> 04:21.262
Oh, my gosh.

04:21.262 --> 04:22.396
Chinese dumpling drama.

04:22.397 --> 04:24.065
- So... bye-bye.
- Save me some dumplings.

04:24.066 --> 04:26.134
Look, he doesn't know anything about us,

04:26.135 --> 04:27.268
so just relax.

04:27.269 --> 04:28.636
Absolutely... just on a different floor.

04:28.637 --> 04:31.539
Hey, it is really crazy in there.

04:31.540 --> 04:32.740
Never get between government workers

04:32.741 --> 04:34.609
and free food.

04:34.610 --> 04:35.743
Babe, this is Matt.

04:35.744 --> 04:36.844
Oh! The famous Matt.

04:36.845 --> 04:38.546
- Win Barrington.
- Nice to meet you.

04:38.547 --> 04:40.114
I know, I know, I look
like a walking stereotype.

04:40.115 --> 04:41.349
Right?

04:41.350 --> 04:43.249
Medical marijuana
lobbyist with the munchies.

04:45.554 --> 04:46.988
Daisy's told me

04:46.989 --> 04:48.756
so much about you.

04:48.757 --> 04:50.424
- Has she?
- Oh, yeah.

04:50.425 --> 04:51.958
Wow.

04:53.527 --> 04:54.894
Dumpling?

04:57.598 --> 04:59.207
Obviously, Prime Minister Arif

04:59.208 --> 05:01.131
will be immediately to your right, but...

05:01.132 --> 05:03.444
...Hasan, defense minister, already hates

05:03.445 --> 05:05.079
that a Sunni is Prime Minister,

05:05.080 --> 05:06.647
when the Shia have three
times the population.

05:06.648 --> 05:08.416
So he'll be damned if he's going to be

05:08.417 --> 05:09.750
tucked away to the right of Arif

05:09.751 --> 05:12.486
while the new oil minister, Barakat,

05:12.487 --> 05:14.021
who's a Kurd, is on my left.

05:14.022 --> 05:15.156
Am I right?

05:15.157 --> 05:16.624
Now you're just messing with me.

05:16.625 --> 05:17.992
But the Kurds are the only

05:17.993 --> 05:20.094
really reliably pro-Western contingent.

05:20.095 --> 05:21.262
Yeah. Not to mention

05:21.263 --> 05:23.397
the most effective fighters against ISIS.

05:23.398 --> 05:24.899
So there's a case to be made for Barakat

05:24.900 --> 05:27.668
to be in the second most prestigious spot,

05:27.669 --> 05:28.293
on your left.

05:28.294 --> 05:30.368
Well, good thing they
haven't all been on a plane

05:30.369 --> 05:31.739
for 15 hours together.

05:31.740 --> 05:34.308
Otherwise, they might be edgy or something.

05:34.309 --> 05:37.111
I mean, if these guys can't
even manage a photograph,

05:37.112 --> 05:38.545
I don't know how they're going to form

05:38.546 --> 05:40.614
an integrated army against ISIS.

05:40.615 --> 05:42.416
Well, the fact that they
all traveled here together

05:42.417 --> 05:43.717
is a great sign,

05:43.718 --> 05:46.120
and the picture will send
an important signal of unity.

05:46.121 --> 05:47.888
If their new government doesn't collapse

05:47.889 --> 05:49.289
when someone makes bunny ears.

05:49.290 --> 05:51.024
Ma'am, your daughter's here.

05:51.025 --> 05:52.359
I see that.

05:52.360 --> 05:53.427
Hi.

05:53.428 --> 05:54.695
Well, they're probably downstairs,

05:54.696 --> 05:56.830
- so I will send them up.
- Good.

05:56.831 --> 05:57.798
Hi.

05:57.799 --> 05:58.932
You on break or something?

05:58.933 --> 06:01.068
Okay, you were right.

06:01.069 --> 06:03.073
- Let's get that over with.
- You're going back to college?

06:03.074 --> 06:04.561
- Not funny.
- Sorry.

06:04.562 --> 06:05.439
About my shirt.

06:05.440 --> 06:07.741
My manager told me that I had to change.

06:07.742 --> 06:10.143
He even used the words "too casual".

06:10.144 --> 06:11.878
So if you want to gloat,
just get it over now.

06:11.879 --> 06:12.813
I'm not gloating.

06:12.814 --> 06:14.047
I didn't want to be right.

06:14.048 --> 06:15.682
Okay, well, if I had listened to you,

06:15.683 --> 06:17.851
then I wouldn't be here
now, asking you for $50.

06:17.852 --> 06:18.915
Fifty dollars?

06:18.916 --> 06:20.257
I can't go all the way back home.

06:20.258 --> 06:22.055
I mean, I would miss half of my shift.

06:22.056 --> 06:23.884
And all of my front of
house clothes are dirty.

06:23.885 --> 06:25.022
I don't know if I have the cash.

06:25.023 --> 06:27.127
- I-I just didn't plan ahead.
- What about your credit card?

06:27.128 --> 06:29.262
- I think we can call this an emergency.
- It's maxed out.

06:29.263 --> 06:31.974
Your emergency credit card is maxed out?

06:31.975 --> 06:32.688
Mom.

06:32.689 --> 06:34.428
Did I sleep through some
emergencies along the way?

06:34.429 --> 06:35.482
- Can you not?
- I have a right to ask

06:35.483 --> 06:36.736
- where our money has gone.
- Ma'am?

06:36.737 --> 06:37.804
- Okay, pl...
- Ma'am.

06:37.805 --> 06:40.565
The Iraqi delegation has arrived.

06:40.941 --> 06:42.943
Thank you.

06:42.944 --> 06:44.577
Please don't give me that look.

06:44.578 --> 06:47.147
I cannot put a foot right with you.

06:47.148 --> 06:48.648
It's exhausting to live with.

06:48.649 --> 06:49.649
You want me to move out?

06:49.650 --> 06:51.317
No. God...

06:51.318 --> 06:53.420
Can we do this later? Please?

06:53.421 --> 06:54.754
Or not at all, maybe?

06:54.755 --> 06:56.256
I mean, if you want
to... we-we don't have to.

06:56.257 --> 06:57.257
I don't want to.

06:57.258 --> 06:59.192
I love you.

06:59.193 --> 07:00.460
- We're good?
- Sure.

07:00.461 --> 07:01.827
Good.

07:05.164 --> 07:07.924
And her she is now. Secretary McCord.

07:10.203 --> 07:11.204
Um...

07:11.205 --> 07:13.239
wh-where can I get a blouse

07:13.240 --> 07:14.707
near here for $50?

07:14.708 --> 07:17.343
I don't think you can.

07:17.344 --> 07:19.012
Although the gift shop
downstairs sells T-shirts

07:19.013 --> 07:20.745
that say "State of Confusion.”

07:21.881 --> 07:23.349
God, I'm running out of time.

07:23.350 --> 07:25.418
I am so gonna get fired.

07:25.419 --> 07:27.120
Well, uh...

07:27.121 --> 07:29.155
I have an extra... like, a dressier blouse

07:29.156 --> 07:31.090
that I keep in a stash for your mom.

07:31.091 --> 07:32.225
Maybe that'll work?

07:32.226 --> 07:34.960
Yeah. Okay, thanks.

07:36.062 --> 07:37.530
I guess I just groveled for nothing.

07:37.531 --> 07:40.233
Well, it's good training
for a career in Washington.

07:40.234 --> 07:42.535
Well, yeah. Not interested.

07:42.536 --> 07:43.603
Smart girl.

07:43.604 --> 07:46.239
"Win.”

07:46.240 --> 07:47.473
What kind of stupid name is...

07:47.474 --> 07:49.308
Hey, Matty.

07:49.309 --> 07:50.343
Win!

07:50.344 --> 07:52.510
Hey.

07:54.380 --> 07:55.481
Daisy's not here.

07:55.482 --> 07:57.550
Obviously.

07:57.551 --> 07:59.115
She's probably down in the press room.

07:59.116 --> 08:00.641
I didn't actually come here today

08:00.642 --> 08:01.819
to speak to her.

08:02.922 --> 08:05.524
Because you came for the dumplings?

08:05.525 --> 08:06.559
I came to speak to you.

08:06.560 --> 08:08.494
Oh?

08:08.495 --> 08:10.563
Why is, um, why's that?

08:10.564 --> 08:12.031
Well, it's about Daisy.

08:12.032 --> 08:13.532
Well,

08:13.533 --> 08:15.835
you and Daisy.

08:17.237 --> 08:18.703
May I?

08:22.641 --> 08:24.076
All right.

08:24.077 --> 08:25.778
How about this one?

08:25.779 --> 08:27.613
A little too Dolly Madison.

08:27.614 --> 08:29.715
Waiters can't be choosers.

08:29.716 --> 08:31.316
I'm a hostess.

08:31.317 --> 08:33.251
Oh. Not for long, if you don't get going.

08:33.253 --> 08:36.255
All right, you're gonna wear this one.

08:36.256 --> 08:38.256
- Thanks.
- Mmm.

08:38.258 --> 08:40.725
Oh, I wish you were my assistant.

08:41.527 --> 08:43.006
I don't.

08:45.664 --> 08:49.434
Blake, any calls about the Meat Market?

08:49.435 --> 08:50.602
The... I'm sorry?

08:50.603 --> 08:52.771
Today is the first day
of a week-long period

08:52.772 --> 08:54.206
where the department matches

08:54.207 --> 08:55.707
its Foreign Service officers

08:55.708 --> 08:56.775
with their postings abroad.

08:56.776 --> 08:58.210
Yeah, I'm aware of that.

08:58.211 --> 09:00.445
I just wasn't aware that we
called it "The Meat Market.”

09:00.446 --> 09:02.948
Every year, a few officers
are unhappy with their postings

09:02.949 --> 09:04.649
and they call up here to complain.

09:04.650 --> 09:08.086
Shouldn't that be a Bureau
of Human Resources problem?

09:08.087 --> 09:11.757
Human Resources, in their
habitual defensive crouch,

09:11.758 --> 09:15.393
tends to lead these
unhappy officers to believe

09:15.394 --> 09:17.829
there is wiggle room when
it comes to their postings,

09:17.830 --> 09:18.997
but there is not.

09:18.998 --> 09:22.501
Well, no one's complained yet, so...

09:22.502 --> 09:24.222
maybe they're still busy eating their ymer.

09:27.072 --> 09:28.173
Have anyone who calls

09:28.174 --> 09:30.475
about a difficult posting come up here.

09:30.476 --> 09:32.010
I'll deal with them myself.

09:32.011 --> 09:33.410
Okay.

09:33.540 --> 09:36.255
Prime Minister Arif.

09:36.256 --> 09:38.216
Minister Hasan.

09:38.217 --> 09:40.251
Minister Barakat.

09:40.252 --> 09:42.620
It is a hopeful sign

09:42.621 --> 09:44.789
for your proud nation
and the rest of the world

09:44.790 --> 09:48.026
that you've traveled here together.

09:48.027 --> 09:51.396
We welcome you to the United States.

09:53.666 --> 09:56.267
"Thank you so much for
your gracious words.”

09:56.268 --> 09:58.303
Insh'Allah, we will welcome you

09:58.304 --> 10:00.471
to a peaceful Iraq

10:00.472 --> 10:02.073
one day very soon.

10:02.074 --> 10:03.741
I look forward to it.

10:03.742 --> 10:06.377
If you could please direct
your attention to the camera?

10:06.378 --> 10:08.446
You have never been to Iraq before,

10:08.447 --> 10:10.615
Madam Secretary?

10:10.616 --> 10:12.315
No, I haven't.

10:13.618 --> 10:15.019
Mike Hirst. Welcome to The Sandbox.

10:15.020 --> 10:16.320
Oh, thanks, Mike.

10:16.321 --> 10:17.688
They speak highly of you at Langley.

10:17.689 --> 10:19.524
Yeah, the brass is big on you, too.

10:19.525 --> 10:20.658
Best analyst they got.

10:20.659 --> 10:22.026
A real killer, they say.

10:22.027 --> 10:23.995
- Well, I don't know about that.
- Yeah, neither do I...

10:23.996 --> 10:25.963
'cause out here, we are real killers.

10:25.964 --> 10:27.565
And quite frankly, I don't
know what I'm gonna do

10:27.566 --> 10:29.000
with another desk jockey from Langley.

10:29.001 --> 10:30.134
Depends on how badly

10:30.135 --> 10:31.936
you want Safeer Al-Jamil, I guess.

10:31.937 --> 10:33.437
Son of a bitch has
blown up half of Baghdad,

10:33.438 --> 10:34.639
so yeah, I want him.

10:34.640 --> 10:35.906
And, look, while I appreciate

10:35.907 --> 10:37.429
your new Intel, I'm gonna
tell you something...

10:37.430 --> 10:39.477
That's right, Mike... my new Intel.

10:39.478 --> 10:41.712
I've been tracking
Safeer for two years now,

10:41.713 --> 10:44.115
so when we bring him in, based on my Intel,

10:44.116 --> 10:45.950
Langley wants me to interrogate him.

10:45.951 --> 10:47.084
We clear about that?

10:47.085 --> 10:48.753
Yes, sir.

10:48.754 --> 10:49.753
A real killer.

10:51.022 --> 10:52.456
Get away from the windows!

10:52.457 --> 10:53.691
What's going on?

10:53.692 --> 10:54.792
We've got an active shooter

10:54.793 --> 10:55.993
- situation, ma'am.
- Wh...

10:55.994 --> 10:56.861
We're in a lockdown.

10:56.862 --> 10:57.893
All we know is, he's armed

10:57.894 --> 10:59.630
and he's outside. Until
we know it's safe...

10:59.631 --> 11:01.198
- What about Stevie?
- We found her, ma'am.

11:01.199 --> 11:02.679
She's safe.

11:04.012 --> 11:11.576
Sync and corrections by awaqeded
- www.addic7ed.com -

11:19.760 --> 11:21.504
Alice Millevoi?

11:21.505 --> 11:24.112
- Um, yes?
- Do you know who I am?

11:24.113 --> 11:25.741
You're the secretary's chief of staff.

11:25.742 --> 11:28.410
So you know how busy I
am. Let's cut to the chase.

11:28.411 --> 11:31.012
Your assignment to
Portugal has been cancelled,

11:31.013 --> 11:32.948
and you've been reassigned to Angola.

11:32.949 --> 11:34.482
- What? I...
- You are the only person

11:34.483 --> 11:36.218
available with the experience

11:36.219 --> 11:37.519
and language skills required,

11:37.520 --> 11:40.021
so there is no room for appeal.

11:40.022 --> 11:41.590
But I've looked at your file,

11:41.591 --> 11:43.758
and you are well-prepared
to handle this post.

11:43.759 --> 11:44.759
I'm sorry,

11:44.760 --> 11:45.961
but the decision is final.

11:45.962 --> 11:47.696
So if you'll excuse me,

11:47.697 --> 11:49.331
I have other matters to tend to.

11:49.332 --> 11:50.517
Sorry, ma'am, but I'm a bit confused.

11:50.518 --> 11:52.552
- I was assured...
- We all have our disappointments,

11:52.553 --> 11:53.601
Ms. Millevoi.

11:53.602 --> 11:56.436
Thank you for your service,
and good luck in Angola.

